         <entryFree xml:id="k000265" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000265-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt" source="#biblk000265-1">dangongzao</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000265-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">單栱造</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000265-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">单栱造</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000265-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin" source="#biblk000265-2">dāngǒngzào</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000265-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">tan-kung-tsao</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000265-6" xml:lang="en">bracket</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000265</idno>
            <note type="Gloss">
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000265-3">Literally "single bracket arm construction," in dangongzao (also dangong zao) single bracket arms parallel to the building plane are used to support beams, as do linggong <term ref="/keyword/k000156">令栱</term>, rather than adding another layer of, typically larger, bracket arms, such as mangong <term ref="/keyword/k000155">慢栱</term> （Li 2009, 4.3a; 17.12a). In the Yingzao fashi 《營造法式》 (1103), this term could be used in contrast to "chonggong <term ref="/keyword/k000257">重栱</term>" or "chonggong zao 重栱造" where an upper layer of bracket arms was used (Li 2009, 11.3b). </p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000265">
               </p>
            </note>
            <note type="related concepts">
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000257">重栱 chónggǒng</term></p>
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000256">單栱 dāngǒng</term></p>
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000156">令栱 lìnggǒng</term></p>
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000155">慢栱 màngǒng</term></p>
            </note>
